# Navigation Design

> **Reference**: This guide extends the [UX/UI Design Principles](ux-ui.mdc). Make sure you're familiar with core UX/UI principles before diving into navigation specifics.

## üìã Overview

Navigation is the roadmap of your website‚Äîit helps users find what they need and understand where they are. Well-designed navigation is intuitive, consistent, and accessible. Confusing navigation is one of the most common reasons users abandon websites.

**Why it matters:**
- Confusing navigation increases abandonment and support requests.
- Good navigation improves discovery, time-on-site, and conversion.

## üéØ Core Navigation Principles

### 1. Clarity
- Use clear, descriptive labels
- Avoid jargon and internal terminology
- Make links obviously clickable
- Show current location

### 2. Consistency
- Keep navigation in the same place
- Use consistent styling
- Maintain hierarchy across pages
- Predictable interaction patterns

### 3. Simplicity
- Limit top-level items (5-7 maximum)
- Group related items logically
- Use progressive disclosure
- Avoid deep hierarchies (max 3 levels)

### 4. Accessibility
- Keyboard navigable
- Screen reader friendly
- Clear focus indicators
- ARIA landmarks and labels

